[
    {
        "content": "<p>Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">^</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\widehat{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.92333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.92333em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"width:calc(100% - 0.16668em);margin-left:0.16668em;top:-3.6833299999999998em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span style=\"height:0.24em;\"><svg height=\"0.24em\" preserveAspectRatio=\"none\" viewBox=\"0 0 1062 239\" width=\"100%\"><path d=\"M529 0h5l519 115c5 1 9 5 9 10 0 1-1 2-1 3l-4 22 c-1 5-5 9-11 9h-2L532 67 19 159h-2c-5 0-9-4-11-9l-5-22c-1-6 2-12 8-13z\"></path></svg></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> be the category of presheaves on a small category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>I know all representable presheaves are <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compact_object_(mathematics)\">finitely presented</a> objects of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">^</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\widehat{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.92333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.92333em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"width:calc(100% - 0.16668em);margin-left:0.16668em;top:-3.6833299999999998em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span style=\"height:0.24em;\"><svg height=\"0.24em\" preserveAspectRatio=\"none\" viewBox=\"0 0 1062 239\" width=\"100%\"><path d=\"M529 0h5l519 115c5 1 9 5 9 10 0 1-1 2-1 3l-4 22 c-1 5-5 9-11 9h-2L532 67 19 159h-2c-5 0-9-4-11-9l-5-22c-1-6 2-12 8-13z\"></path></svg></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>In any category, any finite colimit of finitely presented objects is again finitely presented.</p>\n<p>So, any finite colimit of representables is a finitely presented object of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">^</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\widehat{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.92333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.92333em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"width:calc(100% - 0.16668em);margin-left:0.16668em;top:-3.6833299999999998em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span style=\"height:0.24em;\"><svg height=\"0.24em\" preserveAspectRatio=\"none\" viewBox=\"0 0 1062 239\" width=\"100%\"><path d=\"M529 0h5l519 115c5 1 9 5 9 10 0 1-1 2-1 3l-4 22 c-1 5-5 9-11 9h-2L532 67 19 159h-2c-5 0-9-4-11-9l-5-22c-1-6 2-12 8-13z\"></path></svg></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p><strong>Question:</strong> if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"true\">^</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\in \\widehat{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.92333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.92333em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span><span class=\"svg-align\" style=\"width:calc(100% - 0.16668em);margin-left:0.16668em;top:-3.6833299999999998em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span style=\"height:0.24em;\"><svg height=\"0.24em\" preserveAspectRatio=\"none\" viewBox=\"0 0 1062 239\" width=\"100%\"><path d=\"M529 0h5l519 115c5 1 9 5 9 10 0 1-1 2-1 3l-4 22 c-1 5-5 9-11 9h-2L532 67 19 159h-2c-5 0-9-4-11-9l-5-22c-1-6 2-12 8-13z\"></path></svg></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is a finitely presented object, is it a finite colimit of representables?</p>",
        "id": 198397299,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1590109909
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277473\">@Morgan Rogers</span> and I just used this in our paper, but only in the case where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> has only one object.<br>\nAs reference we used: <br>\nAdámek and Rosicky, \"Locally Presentable and Accessible Categories\", Corollary 3.13.<br>\nThe result holds for arbitrary varieties of finitary algebras.<br>\nAfter your helpful comments in <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-basic.20questions/topic/Terminology.20for.20finitary.20algebraic.20theory/near/198118875\">\"basic questions : finitely presentable objects\"</a>, I think they include many-sorted finitary algebras in their definition.<br>\nSo I would guess this includes the case you are interested in?</p>",
        "id": 198409089,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1590128205
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Some details (mostly for myself):<br>\nCorollary 3.13 shows that finitely presentable objects (in the topos-theoretic sense) are finitely presentable in the sense of universal algebra, i.e. they are a finite colimit of finitely generated free objects.<br>\nSo it remains to show that the free objects are themselves finite colimits of representables. In fact, as maybe suspected, they are finite coproducts of representables.<br>\nTo show this, it is enough to show that finite coproducts of representables satisfy the universal property of the free algebra, as given in Corollary 3.3 of loc.cit. (it says the free algebra construction is left adjoint to the functor that sends a many-sorted algebra to its set of elements, seen as object of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">s</mi></mrow><mi>S</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{Sets}^S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.917341em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">s</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.917341em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1390100000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> the set of sorts).</p>",
        "id": 198420186,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1590138342
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Aurielen Damien answered my question on MathOverflow:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/361282/are-compact-objects-in-presheaf-categories-finite-colimits-of-representables\">Are compact objects in presheaf categories finite colimits of representables?</a>.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 198700720,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1590439004
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But the proof goes by a bit quick for me.   How do you get that split mono, exactly?</p>",
        "id": 198700841,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1590439109
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The split mono comes from factoring the identity map from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> to the colimit of the filtered diagram (also <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>) through some object of the diagram, as provided by the finite presentability hypothesis.</p>",
        "id": 198701957,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1590440277
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>However, the proof ends a bit abruptly since you asked for a finite colimit of representables, not a finite colimit of finite colimits of representables.</p>",
        "id": 198702007,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1590440304
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's not hard to rectify this, but this uses the fact that you're specifically dealing with a category of presheaves and not an arbitrary locally finitely presentable category</p>",
        "id": 198702020,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1590440341
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks!  Are you saying we can't in general write a finite colimit of finite colimits of X's as a finite colimit of X's (where \"X\" is some class of objects)?</p>",
        "id": 198702724,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1590441195
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, for example: <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/204792/is-every-abelian-group-a-colimit-of-copies-of-z\">https://mathoverflow.net/questions/204792/is-every-abelian-group-a-colimit-of-copies-of-z</a></p>",
        "id": 198702834,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1590441266
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess that's only an answer to your question with \"finite\" removed, but I assume the answer would be the same...</p>",
        "id": 198702952,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1590441450
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ooh, this is a nice fact to keep in my pocket</p>",
        "id": 198705742,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1590445223
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The rest of the proof goes like this: we've represented our object as a coequalizer <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>⇉</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B \\rightrightarrows A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.86413em;vertical-align:-0.1808em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⇉</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span> of two maps between objects that are each finite colimits of representables. We may replace <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> with an object that surjects onto <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>, say the coproduct of all the objects in the diagram which constructs it as a colimit of representables. So, we may assume that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> is a finite coproduct of representables. I'll just treat one representable at a time.</p>",
        "id": 198705841,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1590445400
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A map from a representable to the colimit of a diagram (here, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span>) factors through one of the objects of the diagram (basically because colimits are computed objectwise). This is where we use the fact that we are working in a presheaf category. Then, we can replace each map from a representable in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span> with an additional map in the diagram constructing <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span>, and this expresses our original object as the colimit of a finite diagram of representables.</p>",
        "id": 198705976,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1590445573
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yay!  It'll take me a while to fully absorb this - I'm thinking about something very different today - but I'll definitely put in the time needed to do it.  I need this fact for a paper I'm writing!   I'd better remember to acknowledge you.</p>",
        "id": 198706055,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1590445732
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Todd Trimble has given a different proof that finitely presentable (=compact) objects in a presheaf category are precisely the finite colimits of representables, here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Todd Trimble, <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/363087/2893\">Are compact objects in presheaf categories finite colimits of representables?</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>He uses Gabriel-Ulmer duality in a nice way.</p>",
        "id": 200950334,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1592257685
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Finitely.20presentable.20objects/near/200950334\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Todd Trimble has given a different proof that finitely presentable (=compact) objects in a presheaf category are precisely the finite colimits of representables, here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Todd Trimble, <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/363087/2893\">Are compact objects in presheaf categories finite colimits of representables?</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>He uses Gabriel-Ulmer duality in a nice way.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The corresponding (more general) statement for any small strongly generating subcategory of f.p. objects of a l.f.p. 1-category is theorem 7.2 (i) of Kelly's <a href=\"http://www.numdam.org/article/CTGDC_1982__23_1_3_0.pdf\">Structures defined by finite limits in the enriched context, I (Cahiers 1982)</a>.</p>",
        "id": 201595652,
        "sender_full_name": "Chaitanya Leena Subramaniam",
        "timestamp": 1592826470
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Great, thanks!  This generalization may be what I'm really looking for.  I was thinking about the case of presheaf categories just because I couldn't make any progress on more general l.f.p categories!</p>",
        "id": 201638217,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1592848044
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But the closure of G under finite colimits isn't the same as the class of objects which can be written as a finite colimit of objects of G, at least not a priori.</p>",
        "id": 201640808,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1592849347
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Whoops, you're right.  Kelly talks about the \"closure under finite colimits\", but I guess that allows <em>iterated</em> finite colimits.</p>",
        "id": 201648409,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1592853230
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think Todd Trimble's argument is really the same proof, but packaged more neatly into known results. Notably, the argument in section 5.9 of Kelly's Basic Concepts of Enriched Category Theory uses the same computation about coequalizers of colimits of representables to show that in the case of a presheaf category, the generation under finite colimits finishes after a single stage.</p>",
        "id": 201648783,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1592853446
    }
]